👇🏾PLEASE READ THESE GUIDELINES 👇🏾
⠀
Guidelines:
⠀
**BLACK FEMMES TO THE FRONT**
⠀
1. Black people: You never need a reason to put your payment info. Don’t feel obligated to share more than just that!
⠀
2. You can also give! Black folks giving to each other is something we do anyway, feel free to do that here as well.
⠀
White and NBPOC:
⠀
1. Put a 💕 under the person you gave to, this is to spread the coin throughout the post and not to just the first 100 people who respond. If someone already has a 💕 doesn’t mean you can’t give to them! I will message you if you put a 💕 and don’t send $$, don’t try it.
⠀
2. Please share this post in your stories if you give and if you did not, someone you know will give!
⠀
3. Don’t tell folks you gave, it’s not about you.
⠀
4. Continue to agitate and demand the state give reparations to Black people.
⠀
*This is NOT reparations, reparations are owed from the state to Black people. Organizing for reparations is ongoing and I don’t want this post to diminish that specific ask.*

node.text:
FATIMA JAMAL IS THE WRITER AND DIRECTOR of the film No Fats, No Femmes. Her practice considers those [of us] discarded (“the least of these”) and disappeared from Black collective imaginings and networks of care. Her art is where she pours out her feelings and assumes the work of getting her house in order—a “balm in Gilead.” She believes that we are better healed and whole than distracted and entertained.

She wonders where in the world Black trans women are truly safe.

node.text:
Elle Hearns (@soulfreedreams ) is an organizer, speaker, strategist, and writer. Elle’s voice as a strategist community organizer and speaker were formed from her upbringing in Columbus, Ohio as a youth organizer. Ms. Elle currently is the Executive Director of The Marsha P. Johnson (@mpjinstitute )Institute an organization founded in 2015 that works to create a crucial entry point for Black transgender women to advocate for an end to violence against all trans people through advocacy, transformative organizing, restoration, civil disobedience and direct action. The organization is credited for organizing the first ever National Day of Action for Black Trans Women in response to the murders of Amber Monroe, Kandis Capri, and Elisha Walker and held organized events in multiple cities including New York City, Chicago, and Washington DC.

Joshua Allen (they/them) @joshuaobawole is an artist, writer and activist from Brooklyn, New York. They are currently serving as Activist-In-Residence at the NY LGBT Center, building out a mentorship program for the next generation of young leaders and activists. Born and raised in South Central, Los Angeles, Vanessa Rochelle Lewis (@the.ugly.black.woman )(MFA) is a Queer, Fat, Black, Femme performer, facilitator, educator, writer, activist, healer, joyful weirdo, and Faerie Princess Mermaid Gangsta for The Revolution. Vanessa has danced across many professional and creative stages. She has been a Writer and Co-Managing Editor for acclaimed feminist magazines; a community college instructor at multiple Bay Area schools and radical transformative justice programs; a fundraiser and events coordinator for the Queer Women of Color Media Arts Project; the Artist In Residence for the Young Women Freedom Center where she facilitated Art Healing Workshops and a Master Class for formerly incarcerated women, trans, and non-binary people; and so much more. She is currently a core team member for Creating Freedom Movements (a year long social education project that supports grassroots visionary leaders to incubate healing and joy projects while learning more about the art, theory, and practice of social justice movements) and a Creative and Programming Consultant for the Positive Results Center (a family run organization founded by Lewis’s mother, Kandee Rochelle Lewis, to create awareness and prevent the trauma that comes from experiencing bullying, sexual abuse, dating, domestic or inter-personal violence and sex trafficking)
⠀
⠀
Vanessa Is the Founding Director of Reclaim UGLY: Uplift Glorify Love Yourself – And Create A World Where Others Can As Well! The Reclaim UGLY Healing Retreat and Transformative Imagination Conference in February 2022 - and so many transformative events between now and then (Like a free, online open mic and dream  and healing space for Black MaGes this Sat 2/27! Register here: bit.ly/reclaimUGLYopenmic). Stay updated at www.reclaimugly.org !!
⠀
Vanessa’s book Reclaim UGLY: Uplift Glorify Love Yourself And Create A World Where Others Can As Well will be published by North Atlantic Press and dispersed by Penguin Random House in October 2021 so stay tuned!!

Mia Wright-Ross (@mwrcollection) is a leathercraft’s artist and designer, who focuses her works in footwear & accessory design, sculpture, and lifestyle tools. She is the creative director and founder of MWR Collection, a luxury lifestyle artisan atelier based in New York City, and currently sold in Japan. She has also been a leading designer for a number of contemporary designer brands, including Calvin Klein, 3.1 Phillip Lim, Saks 5th Avenue, and Tibi. At Tibi, she was the Senior Footwear & Accessories Designer, where she oversaw all design & development in Italy & Brazil for 4 years. Presently, she is Adjunct Professor  at Parsons The New School of Design, a Freelance Footwear & Accessories Consultant for multiple brands,  and the 2020-21 Artist Fellow at The Museum of Art & Design. Her design client list includes J. Cole, CVSolange, Robert Glasper, Carmelo Anthony, Jimmy Butler, and work has been published in Footwear News, Harper’s Bazaar, Ebony Magazine, & Vogue.

Tracie Q. Gilbert, PhD (she/they) @thembianaiya is an educator, writer, researcher and consultant who uses conversation to help achieve sexual wellness and healing for Black people. Using a wide range of interactive, high-quality workshops and conversation series, Dr. Gilbert flips the script on “The Talk”, helping Black communities unpack the mental, historical, and cultural barriers that keep them from having honest, productive conversations about sex and sexuality.

Dr. Gilbert has nearly 25 years experience teaching urban youth, young adults, and their advocates. She received her Masters of Science in Education at the University of Pennsylvania, and her doctorate from the Center for Human Sexuality Studies at Widener University. Her dissertation on the lived experience of sexuality among African Americans won the CHSS 2019 Distinguished Dissertation Prize.

Dr. Gilbert has taught for a number of universities and non-profits, including Widener University, Christiana Healthcare Systems, Evoluer House, the Innovative Learning Institute, and the Center for Sex Education. She is the inaugural Minority Faculty Fellow at Murray State University, where she taught for 2 years in the departments of Psychology and Gender and Diversity Studies.

At present, Dr. Gilbert conducts direct services for youth and teen audiences through her independent agency, Thembi Anaiya, LLC.

C. Riley Snorton (he/they) @c.rileysnorton is a scholar, author, and activist whose work focuses on historical perspectives of gender and race, specifically Black transgender identities. He is the Interim Faculty Director of the Center for the Study of Race, Politics and Culture and a professor of English & Gender and Sexuality Studies at the University of Chicago. They are the author of Nobody is Supposed to Know: Black Sexuality on the Down Low (2014) and Black on Both Sides: A Racial History of Trans Identity (2017). In 2020, with Hentyle Yapp, he edited Saturation: Race, Art and the Circulation of Value.

@mayowasworld is a stand-up comedian, YouTuber, and filmmaker originally from Atlanta, Georgia but currently living in Europe. Mayowa produces content on their YouTube channel: MayowasWorld discussing colorism, anti-blackness, freeform locs, and their experiences as a dark skin black femme.

Graphics by: @neutokyo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Ericka Hart, M.Ed. She/They on July 25, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, standing and outdoors.

node.text: To me, being a non binary femme is a reminder to be soft. To be soft with myself as doing so for others comes second nature. My body has internalized the demand to be resilient/tough/aggressive. Sucking my stomach in has become an act towards having the world see me as worthy. I’ve come to realize they won’t see me that way regardless if it’s sucked in or not, letting my belly hang where it wants to be is a practice of leaving myself alone, allowing me to sit in and with all the ways I am right now, in this moment.

node.text:
Itinerary/unsolicited advice/and small review from two Black queer/trans/enby boos who just completed a cross country roadtrip:
⠀
Itinerary: NYC- DC/Baltimore- Dillon, South Carolina (Ericka’s ancestral home) - Savannah- Daufuskie Island (South Carolina) -Atlanta- Nashville- Memphis- Montgomery New Orleans- Houston- New Mexico- Arizona (Phoenix/Grand Canyon)- California (Joshua Tree/LA/Oakland)
⠀
Miles traveled: 6,218
⠀
1. We had trepidation doing this as two visibly Black folks but what we kept in mind is that Black queer/trans/agender/enby/intersex folks live all over the country. We are not safe ANYWHERE.
⠀
2. I thought we’d listen to at least one podcast, nope we listened to all of our fave Black artists (sprinkled in a few yts) from each place we drove through and visited. This wasn’t easy haha! Required Google but a good way to pass the time.
⠀
3. Highly recommend using weekenders to pack for each stop rather than lugging huge suitcases into each place you stop.
⠀
4. The WAZE app tells you when police are near 👌🏾
⠀
5. It was an absolute joy to see our family and friends as a destination. It made our hearts swell and you’re able to see more of a place through their eyes.
⠀
6. Carry a little protection for safety: sage/Palo Santo/a vintage knife from friends 😉
⠀
7. Turkey jerky or baby carrots (for the vegans LOL) is an easy snack while driving
⠀
8. Prioritize rest! Make sure you don’t book a shipping container 😝 and get at least one place along the way that has a tub.
⠀
9. Scour the internet for Black history and Black owned businesses in every place. I guarantee you, every place across this country has a Black owned something to support, it pays to look. Tap in with the locals.
⠀
10. White people are the same everywhere. They stare. They white compliment. They try to make you feel uncomfortable in a myriad of ways. Handle accordingly and swiftly, hold fast to your joy. It’s your trip, not theirs. It’s your world, not theirs.
⠀
11. Go cross country with the person you love to be with, guaranteed they will still get on your nerves (LOL), but it’s worth it!
⠀
12. We never used the map, def used the cooler.
⠀

node.text: Joshua Tree photo dump. 10/10 would recommend a visit here. I thought Joshua Tree was secluded and was worried when we didn’t get groceries before we arrived, we’d be out of luck. Ha! They got full banks and several grocery stores! Okay! It’s the desert with a side of major (gentrified) city. Our AirBnb gave us recommendations to restaurants and some of them said “locals only”. In predominately white spaces where Black and Indigenous people have been pushed out, it is inaccurate to assert “locals only”. It’s giving “whites only”.

node.text:
My Dad’s cross country roadtrip when he was 19, has been a story I have heard my entire life. He left with his best friends after graduating high school. When they got to LA, they ran out of money so they thought their parents would help them but they were sadly mistaken. Without money but the desire to keep traveling, they joined the military LOL. 
⠀
As my Dad gets older he reminisces more on his life and the experiences he has had. As I took the picture re-enacting his first time, I thought of how much grief he must have that the folks he went cross country with are no longer living. My Dad rarely expresses sadness for very long so his children have mostly just had to infer.
⠀
I didn’t, however, have to infer how much it meant to him that we were there together and how much he wanted Austin (@austin2pr1511 )to be as well.
⠀
I was awe struck witnessing this space. Also gave honor to the communities who are grieving its loss. Wikatata (grand canyon) belongs to the Havasupai and Hualapai peoples.
